text: It is indeed Scores on the Doors then for your Wednesday night once again and we're going to start as ever with the Scottish football and a fairly busy weekend, a bit of a mixed bag. It was Cup weekend in Scotland. We had the quarter-final stages. I'll run through the results with Dundee United 0, Celtic 4, Motherwell 1, Aberdeen 2, Hearts 2, St Mirren 2, Ayr 0, Hibs 2, those four games before others. You see there, Hearts and St Mirren, that one will go to a replay. Also in the SPL, one game to talk about, Inverness, Califisso 1, Kilmarnock 1 was the result in that one. So, fellas, I'll get you off and running for this evening. Your thoughts? Celtic getting through against Dundee United. 4-0 result, but you have to say the red card probably tainted that result, don't you think? I think so. Yep, tainted, definitely. I don't know if I'd use the word tainted, but it helped it. Definitely helped it, aye. You think? Because, I mean, the game was looking very tight. Dundee United were very much in the game. Celtic maybe never got started. But you sense that if Dundee United maybe kept 11 men on the pitch, that it would be a tighter second half. If they'd have kept that world-beater, that star, Robbie Nilsson on it, it would have been a different... No, I think Dundee United are playing well into momentum, so they drained out when they got sent off, and Celtic just sort of took over a wee bit and started the passing game a wee bit and scored a penalty, a jack penalty. I mean, Celtic, that's them through now. They either play Hearts or something. Can you see anyone stopping Celtic? Do you think anyone's got a chance of beating them? Well, I don't know. I don't know. Dundee United done a good job until half-time, and then, obviously, when that Nilsson got sent off, so Celtic's run there isn't going to live forever. No run does. So someone has to stop them, and why not in the Cup? I think you're looking at Hearts, really. I think Hearts are probably one of the strongest teams in SPL right now, and we only beat them by Celtic. I mean, only beat them by the skin of their teeth at Parkhead, the last time they played there. So I think Hearts have a big chance. I think they're going to be taking this out, giving us a game, you know? You say Hearts were unfortunate to get through at the weekend, but you say, Billy, that, I mean, obviously, we know all about Rangers' problems. With Hearts' financial problems not getting paid off, do you think maybe the squad coming together has really helped them taking off the second half of the season? Well, yeah. I think when background trouble starts to creep in, you're looking at the team, the managers, the background staff to come together and try and... It's a really hard job for a manager to... to... to... to... to... to... to... take the players' minds off it, especially when you're talking about wedgies, because it's what pays the bills at the end of the day. So they're just, they become real people when you start talking about that, so try to get them focused. The best thing you can do, especially in a team sport, is get them all together, and that's what they've got to look to do. I mean, on the pitch, I mean, I mean, obviously, as I say, the players have came together, but one player that really stood out the last couple of weeks for Hearts, Craig Beattie. He's been, like, a new player for Hearts. Revelation, man. Revelation. He's not been on the road for a long time. He's not been on the scene up here for a while, but he's come back with a bang for sure. And hopefully see more of that form. Quite exciting to see a striker, you know, in our team outside the big two. I suppose the cynic could say, well, he wasn't a very good Celtic. He's not had much luck recently. So his heart's just maybe his level. I don't know. He scored goals for Celtic, and that's what you want from a striker. So he does the job wherever he goes. And he's coming back up here, playing for a team outside the big two. It's going to make it more exciting, I think, my opinion. You know, it's always good to see a threat outside the real firm and make it a three-horse race. So do you think Levine might think, oh, maybe Scottish potential once again? I don't know. I don't know. Why not? As I've always said this, if a player's playing well in the SPL and the Scottish, why not get a call-up? I suppose, although... Why not Jordan Rhodes, you know? I suppose in the SPL, you look at players like BT, that if they carry on playing well, although hearts are not looking at your top three, but there's teams kicking about there. Obviously, Rangers have had their problems with it. Like some other, I'll try to creep into second place, things like that. I mean, all these players will try to play well. And, you know, maybe Levine should. Take a chance on the SPL players, shouldn't they? Or, you know... It does get happening. No. We're too harsh on Aiton. If a player gets a call-up, you don't get the chance to have a wee bit of a bad game, or he played all right. Remember, he's young, or he's not played that much. We're too harsh on Aiton, especially when it comes to football. You get your chance, you're expected to perform. That's the thing as well. We're no Brazil. All the fans seem to think, you know, less than five stars is not good enough. I mean, we'll talk about Scottish rugby later on, but in the football sense, whether it's... Club level or international level, it's like a sort of case of, well... Pressure. All the pressure, the media and the fans. And, I mean, really, we're just not good enough to be up against... Sort of told you to do that. We don't have to give that much pressure out in the first place. I think we should relax a wee bit. But it's a serious national sport, you know. We're not going to go lax on the players. It's hard to make the media an excuse because it's not going to change. So, if you can't change it, then... Exactly. ...doesn't everyone continue to moan about it? You need to either go away or give up, you know. I think we'll find it hard to stop moaning about Scottish football... ...or whatever. For as long as we live. But also on the Scottish Club at the weekend, Hibs, they've had a poor season all round. I mean, me and I know Kevin Andrews have been here. We've annihilated Hibs all season. They really have been an awful side to watch at times. But the cup run will be good for them. And they've got a chance for a final, haven't they? They've been unbelievable in the sense that they're on the bottom of the league. It's that way you just can't believe that Dunfermline haven't gone over them yet. But you look at Dunfermline and realise there's a worse team than Hibs, unfortunately. But they've made a lot of signings. You know what I'm saying? They've made a lot of signings. But George Claros, that was a huge coup, you know, to get that under the nose of Rangers. You know, that's a huge deal for Hibs. He's a good player. I've looked at him a couple of times. I think he's probably the only bright spot for that team right now. You're looking at maybe... Who's the young full-back we were talking about the other time? See, I said that much about SPL. I honestly do not know anyone outside the old fund. I think a lot of fans, I think sometimes... Louis Stevenson, right? Now, he's another good player they've got. But I don't know. I don't know if Pat Fairman said that. It's a tough job. Although he's come in at a transitional period, you know. He's trying to build a team. A team that wasn't very good. You think that... You have to say Hibs are lucky to have done Fairman being weaker than them. Because, I mean... Otherwise, I mean, Hibs out with SPL. I know they were sort of taking a couple of seasons to get into the SPL originally when it started. But Hibs outside the SPL, no Emery Derby. I mean, that sounds unthinkable, doesn't it? Yeah. That's a sort of... It's a given, isn't it? To get the Emery Derby. But I don't know. It's certainly one that will rumble on. But Hibs... Disastrous season in some sense in the league. Very quickly, we'll talk a lot about Rangers. They never had a game at the weekend, Rangers. But obviously, news developing over the weekend. Obviously, the players seen centrally in the end. Some would say taking the 75% pay cut for some of the top earners. So no real redundancies on the playing side at the moment. And we've also had Paul Murray, next director, and his Blue Knight consortium coming in. There was some rumoured interest for the Far Eastern USA. That's sort of died down. I mean, do you think... I mean, Scott Billy, and people that follow Scottish Football Law Firm a bit more closely as well, that things... I mean, last week, we were on this show talking about this is bad. But I mean, there's a glimmer of hope, don't you think? Maybe behind the scenes? Well, yeah. I think there is. Well, the players have taken their cut and the administrators are there saying, if you take this cut, no one has to lose their job. We don't have to liquidise. And there's always going to be a wee bit of hope. I'm hoping, anyway. I think you can side... outside the field, Scotland. Do you think... Quite a sort of revealing statement yesterday from David Murray saying he was sorry that he was duped by Craig White. Do you feel sorry for David Murray at all? No. No, because he promised us when he was giving the club over, he'd give it to... he'd put it in the safest hands possible. Am I right in saying that? Yeah. I don't feel sorry for anyone that worked behind the scenes because... and it's not just Rangers. Every club... they don't get told absolutely everything. I think they're quite happy. As long as teams are successful, like Rangers are, or they're going to be, the same as Celtic, it's only... it's them that are going to win the league. So the success will hide the cracks. So if people are dipping money here, dipping money there, the success means that the fans won't ask any questions and you'll probably find that a lot of people behind the scenes won't be allowed to ask any questions. They won't be allowed. They won't be allowed to know. Anyway, apart from the wee board who's all winning anyway. I think it's as well, you know, it's people's... forget about all the caterers and cleaners, it's their jobs as well, you know. It's a lot of people that aren't attached to playing football necessarily. You know, it's a big deal, man. So hopefully it gets sorted out. It's certainly something that you... It's got to lie, a wee bit of blame with David Murray, I think. He's just walked away from a bad situation, I think, and took none of the... It's certainly something that... It's certainly something that both sides, the argument there, I mean, something that we'll continue to discuss, I'm sure, most weeks, out of scores, in the doors. If you've got any thoughts on that, do get in touch, at city underscore radio on Twitter, or facebook.com, for us, our scores in the doors. Before we move away from Scottish football, the first trophy of the weekend, League Cup final, Celtic against Comaric. You were on about earlier, Scott, the runs all have to come to an end, I'm beating runs. Is there any prayer at all for Comaric? Yeah. See, I don't like saying it against Comaric and all the other teams that aren't within the top two, because they are good teams. They're just not as good as the top two. You think, if some of the teams like Motherwell, Comaric and that, had just a little bit more dosh, I mean, maybe. Absolutely. Certainly. I mean, you always say, take Celtic and Rangers out of it, and we have said before, it could be disastrous, but, I mean, the other teams, I mean, there are some decent players kicking them out. I mean, they always get overshadowed, certainly, by the old firm. Well, where did Stephen Naismith come from? He came from Comaric, didn't he? Chris Boyd. Chris Boyd. And Lima Colick, around the same Colick. He's been in, been quite a few players in Celtic, like, sometimes, go through that avenue. We went to Hibs for a couple of players, I think Scott Brown. Whittaker, for Hibs. I think for Hibs as well. I mean, to give you the team Hibs had at one point, you know, you've got, Hibs had a decent team a few years ago. You've got, it's in the same team you get Brown, Whittaker, Kevin Thompson, Ian Murray, I think as well, who's still captain at Hibs.
